reviewtext: Gotham City’s favorite vigilante has long been known as “the World’s Greatest Detective.” Matt Reeves is the first director to truly realize that on screen.
I enjoyed Tom Holland as Spider-Man...and Zendaya as MJ but unfortunately I did not like the villain plot...I found it convoluted, predictable and dull
Holland continues to impress, perfectly portraying an awkward boy with incredible superpowers. The comedy in Far From Home is also spot-on.
'Top Gun Maverick' is a one hell of a ride that shouldn't be missed. So hop on and buckle up fast!
For me, The Joker is one of the top features released this year.
Reiterating my love of Scorsese, it's his ability to experiment that makes him a compelling director. Every film he directs is worth the time, and The Irishman lives up to that billing.
Theron turns a stock character into a memorably sinister mix of scorned gold digger and plastic surgery addict. It takes a lot more than a pail of water to wipe out this wicked witch.
It's a very messy movie, but I enjoyed it.
The film achieves a difficult balance. [Full review in Spanish]
Quantumania swings big, but forgets the small stuff, to its own detriment.
Candy-colored Thor: Ragnarok is a retro, dimension-hopping hoot.
[Peyton Reed] does an adequate job mixing the wacky silliness of [Jeff] Loveness’ script with a surprisingly hefty amount of a dark and serious tone this time around.

Knives Out is a brilliant whodunnit film that is so much fun to unwrap and piece together. With a stellar cast, some killer humor, and a mild political undertone - it's surely set to entertain everyone.
With a franchise hit such as Alien, the audience expects a certain amount of formula, and Scott certainly supplies it in the structure of the story and several of the characters.
... while McDonagh's film doesn't lack for gallows humor and pitch-dark stuff, it's in the department of truth that it comes up short.
It is a slow character study that didn't really tell us anything about the characters in the film.
...wheezes by with an inescapable sense of fatigue.
It's a good film that's been forced to rattle around in the Bond universe like a loose cog.
This could well be a commercial success. It's a blockbuster of an American film and it was much needed...
Taken 3 isn't just superficially lazy. That quality is the core of the movie's being.

Villeneuve's vision of DUNE is filled with epic world building. But it's more than just feast for the eyes, it offers something thrilling & thought-provoking. Despite a few quibbles, the ending certainly make me wish we could see part II right away.
While the story isn’t as compelling as it could be, thanks in part to some choppiness of the narrative, the overall arcs are engaging and this really sets up a villain who’s a powerful threat.
The tagline for Taken 3 is 'It Ends Here' and we must all pray that it does.
Echoes with the doubled resonance of the best myths, at once a thrilling adventure and a cautionary tale.
Marvel’s mini-hero is back in a movie that’s all scale, no fun.
Where the film falters, Jonathan Majors is there to lift it up with a genuinely fantastic performance as Kang. The next great Marvel villain has arrived, and somehow surpasses the hype.
For a franchise in need of refreshment, it’s anything but a quantum leap.
"One of the most purely pleasurable movies of the year."
Successfully fusing two unlikely genres, it's both a traditional heist picture and a trenchant political and social commentary.​ (Broad Street Review)
A star turn for Momoa, who leads the ridiculousness of this anarchic, campy superhero outing with serious energy and charm. Another promising move for the DCEU.
This time around, the only thing getting taken is your money.
Ant-Man and The Wasp: Quantumania is pure, indulgent escapism that never forgets comic book movies are supposed to be fun.
The movie ultimately gets more right than wrong, finding the proper balance between spectacle and storytelling.
Crashingly enjoyable, frequently exciting and even, when it wants, borderline witty.
It's the weakest of the trilogy, but Taken 3 kicks just hard enough to survive another day.
... this new adventure isn't as fun as the previous ones, it works only as by-the-book entertainment with more muscles than brains. [Full review in Spanish]
The visual splendor of Rogue One often gets ignored, but few images can haunt an audience like The Death Star coming up over the horizon.
The problems extend from characterization to plot.
Everything about Widows works. There's just no resisting it.
The third Ant-Man installment certainly has some winning elements ... but it feels like it’s doing too much while trying to tackle something far too big.
Taken 3 delivers a stimulating and different story to the franchise, but combines it with unbelievable and poorly presented action sequences (however entertaining they may be).
Mostly it exists as connective tissue between different eras of the MCU, displaying embarrassingly little interest in its own main characters.
Taken 3 ends as it began -- another segment in a bloated, lazily drawn cash cow that offers a few laughs and high octane chases.
Fassbender embraces the surface traits of both these human simulacrums then allows the emotional complications to slowly, subtly emerge as their interactions become more and more discordant.
Fool me once, shame on you. Fool me twice, shame on me. Fool me thrice, and now you're just sequel-baiting.

As with the first two films in this dumb but bombastically watchable franchise, writers Luc Besson and Robert Mark Kamen seemingly put no effort into writing a script that can even remotely hold water.
Even as a celebration of Queen's music, Rhapsody is superficial and unconvincing, functioning only as a collection of mediocre music videos.
"Sit Down and Buckle Up!"
Avengers: Endgame is a masterpiece which not only delivers on every expectation you had but exceeds ones you didn't even think about. This isn't just a movie, it's an experience.

I think Greta Gerwig has tapped into what she loved about Little Women as a kid, but made it feel really relevant. This movie tries really hard to say "Little Women matters today," and I think it succeeds.
Rian Johnson has created a movie that is both quintessentially Star Wars and richer than anything that has come before.

Captain America: Civil War is very much a sequel to Winter Soldier but, regrettably, too long, tryingly complicated and it takes the best part of 75 minutes before it breaks into anything resembling comic exuberance.
Be warned, sequel fanboys: This thing sucks! At 62, Neeson still has a glare that means badass. Nothing else makes a damn lick of sense. The only thing getting taken is the audience.
While there are elements nodding to The Empire Strikes Back, The Last Jedi is no copycat. In its most daring moments, it even tweaks a few series tropes, updating them with a decidedly populist kick.

Thoroughly enjoyed Ant Man And The Wasp: Quantumania. Jonathan Majors is a superstar with Michelle Pfeiffer matching him beat for beat. The world building of the Quantum Realm is stunning. It has the right mix of humor, emotional stakes, action, and awe.
On the whole, Quantamania lacked heart because the actors didn't really have anything to work with, and it felt like Disney/Marvel didn't really care about the film at all.
It's a lot closer to 'Batman Begins' than 'Green Lantern'.
A prologue that desperately seeks to make the irrelevant relevant. [Full review in Spanish]

Quantumania throws every can of paint in the garage at the screen while struggling with tone and convincing character dynamics. Jonathan Majors is an absolute beast as Kang the Conqueror. The MCU's Phase Five starts on uneven footing.
Villeneuve's indulgence in mood and melancholy mount to a conclusion that wastes its compelling premise and wallows in infuriatingly all-consuming sentimentality.
If, in the first 20 minutes of this dreck, you can't spot at least three plot holes big enough to drive a monster truck through, then you're probably on the phone.
While I had fun with this film, I was disappointed. That being said, the movie is worth it just for Jonathan Majors.
They've given us a new sci-fi epic, an immersive cinematic journey that, like its source material, feels poised to endure as one of the genre's great works.
Come for the scenery, and settle in for the next two hours trying to make sense of it. There’s no guarantee that you’ll love it, but what’s the quantum realm without a little uncertainty?
There are fates worse than death, and 2012 is one of them.
Aside from [K-2SO's] killer lines, wonderfully voiced by the indispensable Alan Tudyk, most big satisfactions in this big, big movie come from references to Star Wars adventures you've loved before.
In many ways, this is a stupidly entertaining movie. Intellectually, I suspect I really shouldn’t like this movie so much, but we all need a little more whoosh in our lives.

Zhao digs up something fierce, a little sad, spurred on by a lovely sense of longing and belonging that could be the perfect palate-cleanser after the year we've all just had. Frankly, the open road never looked better.
... this new adventure isn't as fun as the previous ones, it works only as by-the-book entertainment with more muscles than brains. [Full review in Spanish]
These are complex dynamics. It's a reason why Dune has been so tough to crack in this medium. I think Villeneuve has done it.
Where the film falters, Jonathan Majors is there to lift it up with a genuinely fantastic performance as Kang. The next great Marvel villain has arrived, and somehow surpasses the hype.

The majority of moviegoers want to see films led by strong, intelligent characters that are more diverse than just heterosexual white men, especially when they are as thoughtfully and beautifully made as this one.
Ron Howard has ensured that Solo is no embarrassment to the franchise, but the chases and hair's breadth escapes become a little tiresome in a less coherent second half.
Black Widow's name may be on the title, but the true heroes of the 24th entry in the MCU mega-franchise are her supporting characters -- a pack of gonzo Russkie faux relatives.
Taken 3 feels like a perfunctory coda. This time, it's vaguely impersonal.
[It] isn't so much out of gas as it is dragging itself away from the stalled car across the baking desert by its fingernails.
Chazelle has crafted a true modern day classic that reminds us of the power of possibility and of dreams, the belief in love and being in love. It's one of the very best films of the year.

Ant-Man and the Wasp: Quantumania is a solid mid-tier MCU entry. One simply wishes that the film didn’t exist principally to set-up the villain/conflict for the rest of the Phase 5. Did we really need a two hour film just to introduce Kang?
It's neither good nor bad, meaningful or meaningless.
Taken 3 isn't a good movie. Against all logic, it isn't a bad movie, either. Instead, it's so casual and indifferent to itself it lapses into something altogether appalling.
The busy wipes, lively zooms and fast cuts that characterised the earlier gangster flicks are not on display. This is as much the Scorsese of Silence as of Wolf of Wall Street.

For those who recall the warnings He Who Remains gave in Loki (or even simply take a look at the titles the MCU has slated for the next year), it becomes quite clear how the film will end even before it begins.
With his third kidnapping caper, Taken 3, Liam Neeson takes self-parody to new lows and the result is hysterically, enjoyably bad.
Marvel today is an amusement park, expanding, building new rides and attractions, trying, flailing and failing to recapture the magic of the past decade.
Its hilarious, mind-bendingly stupid climax is nearly worth the price of admission alone.

Dune is a long-winded and bloated film typifying what men do to overpower others...they fight. Perhaps Part II wouldn't have been necessary if the writers would have focused on doing one thing...telling the story.
While uncomfortable to watch at times, the acting and writing in "Marriage Story" make the narrative soar.
The zippy, brutal action sequences are gripping, the violence sometimes shocking.

Writer-director Jordan Peele’s mysterious third film, Nope, draws on genre tropes from both alien invasion films and Westerns, but it ends up with something altogether original: a Hollywood spectacle about spectacle.
No obvious connection to Takens passim other than its focus on a middle-aged man who'll punch or shoot anyone with a Slavic accent.
Bong Joon Ho's Cannes Film Festival winner is a flat out masterpiece.
A rousing finale. Epic in scale and in heart.

With a sweeping soundtrack, actual detective work, and a surprising turn by a capable Pattinson leading a great cast, this Caped Crusader is learning to be better than he was yesterday in a city losing hope... a reconstruction of the superhero genre?

This new Ant-Man outing truly lives up to its title. The manic multi-coloured world makes it feel like you’ve just stepped in the Star Wars cantina, while weird and wonderful creatures fill the screen.
Instead of making a sophisticated point, "Wonder Woman 1984" devolves into a typical action-driven superhero yarn. But those elements are mighty well presented.
Earth's Mightiest Heroes get the send off they richly deserve, but with one considerable caveat.
As much a compelling black empowerment story as it is an electrifying commentary on the problems of African-American representation across more than a century of cinema.
Visually, the film is messy and flat; the CGI is shockingly poor and the action looks muddled. At least Quantumania has one of the best casts in a Marvel film.
Kang remains more myth than menace and, save for a few dorky gags and sweet father-daughter moments, it's an easily missable movie.
